\title{\pkg{LargeTreeMonitoring} package}
\description{
\pkg{LargeTreeMonitoring} supports tree-level monitoring from Sentinel-2
time series extracted with Google Earth Engine. It provides tools to
retrieve spectral-index observations for individual tree locations,
preprocess the resulting time series, run multiple breakpoint-detection
algorithms, validate detected breaks, summarize results, and launch an
interactive Shiny workflow. Although the package provides general tools for
time-series analysis and breakpoint detection, its current primary focus is
the detection of large tree loss or removal.
}
\details{
The package is organized around the \code{spidf} object, a data-frame
subclass that stores spectral-index observations and request metadata. A
typical analysis starts by initializing Google Earth Engine with
\code{\link{ltm_start_gee}()}, retrieving a Sentinel-2 time series with
\code{\link{ltm_s2_get_data_point}()}, applying optional preprocessing,
running one or more breakpoint-detection wrappers, and collecting the results
in a \code{\link{ltm_ts_breaks}()} container.
}
\section{Main workflow}{

\enumerate{
\item Initialize Google Earth Engine with \code{\link{ltm_start_gee}()}
and verify the stored session status with
\code{\link{ltm_check_gee_status}()}.
\item Retrieve an \code{spidf} time series with
\code{\link{ltm_s2_get_data_point}()}. Supported spectral indices are
listed in \code{\link{SPECTRAL_INDICES_LIST}}, and supported Sentinel-2
processing levels are listed in \code{\link{PROC_LEVELS_LIST}}.

\item Optionally regularize and smooth the time series with
\code{\link{ltm_regularize_spidf}()},
\code{\link{ltm_apply_moving_quantile}()}, and
\code{\link{ltm_apply_whitaker}()}.

\item Run breakpoint-detection wrappers such as:
\itemize{
\item \code{\link{ltm_ed_detect_breaks}()} – Energy-divisive (\link[ecp:e.divisive]{ecp::e.divisive}),
\item \code{\link{ltm_cpm_detect_breaks}()} – Change Point Models
(\link[cpm:cpmPackage]{cpm::cpm-package}),
\item \code{\link{ltm_bfast01_detect_breaks}()} – BFAST (\link[bfast:bfast-package]{bfast::bfast-package}),
\item \code{\link{ltm_mcp_detect_breaks}()} – our model based on a specific
implementation ob a Bayesian Regression with Multiple Change Points
(\link[mcp:mcp-package]{mcp::mcp-package}),
\item \code{\link{ltm_strucchange_detect_breaks}()} – Structural Change in Linear
Regression Models (\link[strucchangeRcpp:breakpoints]{strucchangeRcpp::breakpoints }), and
\item \code{\link{ltm_wbs_detect_breaks}()} – Wild Binary Segmentation for
multiple change-point detection (\link[wbs:wbs-package]{wbs::wbs-package}).
}

\item Store, inspect, flatten, plot, and summarize results with
\code{\link{ltm_ts_breaks}()}, \code{\link{ltm_add_runs}()},
\code{\link{as.data.frame.ts_breaks}()},
\code{\link{ltm_plot_spidf_ts}()}, \code{\link{plot_valid_breaks}()},
and \code{\link{ltm_summarize_break_df}()}.
}
}

\section{Data model}{

\code{spidf} objects contain at least \code{id}, \code{ti},
\code{masked_vals}, \code{spi}, and \code{cloud_mask} columns. Metadata such
as coordinates, date ranges, tree
identifiers, buffer settings, spectral index, processing level, and
preprocessing status are stored as attributes and can be read or updated with
the grouped \code{spidf} accessor and setter functions documented in
\code{\link{spidf_accessors}} and \code{\link{spidf_setters}}.
}

\section{Break detection and validation}{

Break-detection wrappers return \code{ts_breaks_run} objects. Each wrapper
records the method name, analyzed data column, detected break index and date
when available, the raw upstream algorithm result, seasonal-adjustment
metadata, and validation diagnostics. Long-term and short-term validators
compare pre-break and post-break summaries, while the randomized trend
validator implemented by \code{\link{ltm_trend_validator_randomized}()}
evaluates short-term negative trend evidence around a candidate break.
}

\section{Cache and configuration}{

Cache files are stored under \code{\link{ltm_cache_dir}()}. The cache
location can be configured with option
\code{LargeTreeMonitoring.cache_dir} or environment variable
\code{LTM_CACHE_DIR}; otherwise the package uses the platform-specific R
user cache directory and falls back to the legacy \code{ltm_cache} directory
when needed. User app configuration is stored under
\code{\link{ltm_config_dir}()}.
}

